    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="191"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841D.48/73</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. Robert B. Stewart of the
                        Division of European Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-25">September 25,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Sean Nunan, Counselor, Irish Legation;</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. John D. Hickerson, Eu;<note n="37"
                                xml:id="d191fn37">Division of European Affairs.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Robert B. Stewart, Eu.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Mr. Nunan called at the Department in connection with the Irish Legation’s note
                    of September 22 concerning the proposed purchase by the Irish Government of two
                    ships from the Maritime Commission.</p>
                <pb facs="0257" n="249" xml:id="pg_249"/>
                <p>Mr. Nunan was informed that the questions raised in the Legation’s note had been
                    referred to the authorities of this Government who had been dealing with the
                    matter and that we would pass on to him any further information of interest
                    which might be received by the Department.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
